frequent_values: SONYC is an afterschool program for students in 6th, 7th, and 8th grades. SONYC activities include dance, music, sports, fashion, cooking, and more.

HEAP helps eligible households meet their home energy needs in the winter season. The money can pay for fuel, your utility source, equipment and/or repairs. The City pays the costs either directly to the company (heating benefit and/or utility benefit) or to the household (utility benefit only).

EarlyLearn NYC Head Start programs provide a safe, caring environment for three and four year old children. Care is provided at a center for eight hours a day and children are fed healthy meals and snacks.

If you have a child with physical, mental, or emotional disabilities, ECDCs can help. ECDCs provide information to members of the community about services for young children from birth to age five with diagnosed or suspected special needs.

People who need care can get it at home instead of having to move into a nursing home or institution. There are different types of care for people with different needs. Home Care Services Program can give you a home nurse, house cleaning, physical therapy, and more.

shortest_values: Children under 19 years old can get free or low-cost medical care through Child Health Plus and Children's Medicaid.
SCHE gives property tax help to senior homeowners. It lowers the taxes of seniors who own one to three homes, condos, or coop apartments.
Your family can get cash if you are in need. The funds come on a debit card that you can use at any ATM or store where EBT cards are accepted.
Every New Yorker can get health insurance. There are low-cost and free plans for people who qualify, and counselors to help you choose a plan.
STAR provides property tax relief to New York State's homeowners. It lowers the tax burden on New York residents who live in school districts.
longest_values:
Cornerstone Programs offer NYCHA residents opportunities for fun, learning, and support. Programs for youth and adults include:

  • tutoring
  • college prep
  • English for speakers of other languages and high school equivalency classes
  • workforce development
  • family relationship workshops
  • recreation, dance, and music classes
  • tenant education and advocacy

Programs are located at 94 NYCHA Community Centers throughout the five boroughs.

CUNY ASAP helps students earn an associate degree within three years by providing financial, academic, and personal support. Students benefit from:

  • Free unlimited MetroCards
  • Textbook vouchers to reduce (or eliminate) the cost of textbooks
  • Full-tuition assistance (for students on financial aid)
  • A dedicated ASAP advisor
  • Special registration options and consolidated schedules
  • Career development and academic support

LGBTQ New Yorkers can get quality health care in safe and respectful NYC Health + Hospitals centers. Services include:

  • women\u2019s and men's health
  • transgender health, including gender affirming surgeries and hormone therapy
  • HIV and STD prevention, screening, and treatment
  • social work and behavioral health services
  • primary care

All staff are trained on phsyical, psychological, and social LGBTQ issues.

LGBTQ New Yorkers can get quality health care in safe and respectful NYC Health + Hospitals centers. Services include:

  • women\u2019s and men's health
  • transgender health, including gender affirming surgeries and hormone therapy
  • HIV and STD prevention, screening, and treatment
  • social work and behavioral health services
  • primary care

All staff are trained on physical, psychological, and social LGBTQ issues.

Youth can get care at NYC Health + Hospitals clinics. Services include:

  • sexual and reproductive health care
  • primary care
  • mental health and depression help
  • LGBTQ care
  • healthy weight management
  • sports physical and sports injury care

Care is open to all youth, regardless of ability to pay, immigration status, disability, sexual orientation, or gender identity/expression.

To be eligible for Veterans' Exemption, you should be able to answer yes to all of these questions.

  • Are you the current deeded owner, spouse or surviving un-remarried widow/widower of the property owner?
  • Is the property your primary residence?
  • Are you a veteran who served in the US armed forces during one of the following conflicts only:
    • Persian Gulf Conflict (includes the Afghanistan and Iraq Conflicts) - beginning August 2, 1990 to present
    • Vietnam War - February 28, 1961 to May 7, 1975
    • Korean War - June 27, 1950 - January 31, 1955
    • World War II - December 7, 1941 to December 31, 1946
    • World War I - April 6, 1917 to November 11, 1918

frequent_values: NYC Health + Hospitals has centers across the five boroughs. Use the location finder to find a center close to you and call to make an appointment.

• Call DYCD Youth Connect at 800-246-4646 to apply.
  • You can also use Discover DYCD with the "jobs & internships" filter to see what programs are near your home.

• Make an appointment by calling 877-337-2017 and pressing 1 when prompted.
  • When you schedule your appointment, let the staff know if you need:
    • material in large print, Braille, or recorded format
    • a sign language interpreter
    • a personal care attendants to travel with you
    • telephonic interpretation services
  • After you book your appointment you will get an application package in the mail, including the application, a letter about your appointment, and instructions on to schedule your free round-trip transportation to/from the assessment center.
    • When scheduling transportation, please say if you are traveling with a personal care attendant.
  • You can call 877-337-2017 (prompt #1) if you haven't received your AAR eligibility by mail.

How you apply for home care programs depends on your needs. Call the HRA Office of Special Services at 718-557-1399 or visit a Home Care CASA office to find out how to apply to a program right for you and your family.

• If you, or someone you know needs help, you can use the online referral system. Referrals received after 5:00 p.m or during the weekend will be processed the next business day.
  • Call the APS intake unit at 212-630-1853 to make a referral by phone. Referrals can also be made by calling 311 Monday - Friday, 9:00 a.m - 5:00 p.m.
  • You can also submit a referral by emailing APS.

If you are under age 65, you must apply through NY State of Health:

  • Enroll online through NY State of Health website.
  • Call NY State of Health Marketplace at 855-355-5777 or TTY: 800-662-1220 to enroll by phone.
  • Find a free health insurance assistor to help you enroll in person.

If you are age 65 and over, or on Medicare, or need Medicaid related to a disability:

  • Get free in-person assistance to enroll in Medicaid and get help to cover Medicare costs. You may also drop off or mail your completed application and Supplement A form to:
    MAP Initial Eligibility Unit
    PO Box 24390,
    Brooklyn, NY 11202
  • Call the HRA Helpline at 888-692-6116 to enroll by phone.
  • Call Department of Health & Mental Hygiene Enrollers at 347-396-4705 to make an appointment to apply for or renew

To apply for admission to a public high school:

  1. Visit MySchools.nyc and set up your account. Speak with your school counselor if you need help. You will need your:
    • Student ID number
    • Account creation code (PIN)
  2. Use MySchools to explore high school programs based on your interests, location, and more.
  3. Select up to 12 choices to add to your application in your true order of preference, and submit it by the December 14 deadline.

If you just moved to NYC talk to your school counselor or visit a Family Welcome Center.

If you want to apply to a specialized high school, contact your guidance counselor in September to request an admissions ticket for the test.

frequent_values: The City can help you find a website where you can file your taxes for free.
SCRIE/DRIE online applications are temporarily unavailable while we work on a new and improved application. Please use the forms or walk-in location to apply.
There is no online application at this time.

You can submit your application online before going to an enrollment center. To do so:

  1. Go to the IDNYC website.
  2. Select the language you prefer to use.
  3. Read application instructions including eligibility and document requirements.
  4. Fill out the electronic application.
  5. Select the documents you are going to bring to the enrollment center for your appointment.
  6. Schedule an appointment for an enrollment center.
  7. Look over the information you entered and provide an electronic signature.
  8. Print out your application receipt and make sure you bring it to your appointment.

You can use Discover DYCD to find programs in your area. To get started:

  1. Go to the Discover DYCD website.
  2. Select "afterschool programs" in the category field.
  3. Enter your borough and neighborhood, or zip code to begin searching.

longest_values:
1. Go to ACCESS HRA.
  2. Create an ACCESS HRA account or log in to an existing one.
  3. Fill out the SNAP application and submit it.
  4. Send your documents to HRA in one of the following ways.
    1. Scan your documents using the NYC HRA Document Upload app available for free on the iTunes Store (for iPhones) or the GooglePlay Store (for Android phones).
    2. Mail copies of your documents to: PO Box 29008, Brooklyn, NY, 11202-9816.
    3. Take your documents to your local Community Based Organizations (CBOs) to submit to HRA.
  5. After you submit your application, you will be contacted to do an eligibility interview. You can do your interview over the telephone without having to come into a SNAP center.
  6. You can check the status of your application by going to ACCESS HRA.
  7. You will need to recertify for SNAP once every year. The SNAP office will mail you a recertification packet for you to complete and mail back to HRA or recertify online on ACCESS HRA. To apply for admission to a public high school:

  1. Visit MySchools.nyc and set up your account. Speak with your school counselor if you need help. You will need your:
    • Student ID number
    • Account creation code (PIN)
  2. Use MySchools to explore high school programs based on your interests, location, and more.
  3. Select up to 12 choices to add to your application in your true order of preference, and submit it by the December 14 deadline.

If you just moved to NYC talk to your school counselor or visit a Family Welcome Center.

If you want to apply to a specialized high school, contact your guidance counselor in September to request an admissions ticket for the test.

To apply for WIC:

  • Find your local WIC agency, or call the Growing Up Healthy Hotline at 800-522-5006 and ask for the location nearest to you.
  • Gather your income, residency, and identity documents to bring with you.
  • Call the WIC agency where you wish to receive services and make an appointment.
  • A short nutrition assessment will be completed at the time of your appointment by a qualified WIC staff member.

The staff will tell you if you need to bring the WIC Medical Referral Form for you and/or your child completed by your health care provider.

frequent_values:
To apply for Veteran's Exemption, you will need to prove the following:

  • Your Veteran status: Copy of A DD Form 214 ( DD-214) which is the Certificate of Release or Discharge from Active Duty form or separation papers for each veteran. For each disabled veteran, copy of Veterans' Administration letter documenting the disability rating

To apply for Cash Assistance you will need to prove the following:

  • Your identity: such as a photo ID, driver\u2019s license, passport, naturalization certificate, or hospital records.
  • Where you live: such as a statement from your landlord, current rent receipt, lease, or mortgage records.
  • Your income (if any): such as a current pay stub, business records, current income tax return, or an Unemployment Insurance Benefit statement.
  • Citizenship or immigration status: such as your birth certificate, U.S. passport, or military service records.

Check the Cash Assistance document guide to see what else you can use as proof.

To apply for SCRIE, you will need to prove the following:

  • Your age
  • Your rent
  • The income of all household members, which can include: tax returns, Social Security benefits, 1099/W2 statement

To enroll your child in a program, you will need to prove the following:

  • Your child's age
  • Your income, which can include a TANF or SSI benefit letter

To apply for DHE you will need to prove the following:

  • Your income: copies of your federal tax returns and schedules/attachments for all owners. If any owners do not file a tax return, proof of yearly earnings.
  • Your deductions: Copies of receipts for medical or prescription expenses that have not been refunded
  • Your disability status: One of the following for an owner:
    • Copy of the award letter from the Social Security Administration
    • Copy of the award letter from the Railroad Board or the US Postal Service
    • Copy of a certificate from the State Commission for the Blind and Visually Handicapped

shortest_values: There are no required documents at this time; applicants are screened for eligibility by the VA for HUD VASH.
You must bring your child's birth certificate or passport to the G&T test appointment to verify their date of birth.
When you go to the assessment, you will need to bring medical documents that prove your transportation-related disability.
Each health insurance program will require different documents to enroll. Once you decide what insurance option you will enroll in, they will tell you what documents you will need to apply.

  • Your child's age
  • Your income, which can include a TANF or SSI benefit letter

  • Your identity: such as a photo ID, driver\u2019s license, passport, naturalization certificate, or hospital records.

To be found eligible for SNAP you will need to prove the following:

  • Your identity: such as a photo ID, driver\u2019s license, passport, naturalization certificate, or hospital records.
  • Where you live: such as a statement from your landlord, current rent receipt, lease, or mortgage records.
  • Your income (if any): such as a recent pay stub, business records, current tax return, or an Unemployment Insurance Benefit statement.
  • Citizenship or immigration status: such as your birth certificate, U.S. passport, or military service records.
    • Receiving SNAP will not affect your immigration case or lead to deportation.

See the SNAP document guide to see what else you can use as proof.

You will not need to submit any documents to apply for Kindergarten.

After your child receives an offer letter you will be asked to visit the school in person, with your child, and bring the following documents to enroll:

  • Proof of your child's age: birth certificate, passport, record of baptism
  • Two proof of address documents (such as: lease, utility bill, or government issued ID-including IDNYC)
    • Check the "Pre-Registration Checklist" in the NYC Kindergarten Directory to see what other documents you can use.

To apply for EarlyLearn NYC Child Care, you will need to prove the following:

  • Where you live: such as a driver\u2019s license, IDNYC, or utility bill
  • Your income (reason for care documents):
    • If employed: pay stubs and/or CS 1069
    • If self-employed: current income tax documents, notarized statement/accountant statement
    • If attending educational or vocational training: ACD 1082
    • If receiving SSI, Worker\u2019s Compensation, Unemployment Benefits, etc.: proof of income documentation
  • Your citizenship or immigration status: US birth certificate (for children under 18 who live with you), Registration Card (if the child was not born in the US)

To apply for EarlyLearn NYC Child Care, you will need to prove the following:
